text: I think I've finally mastered CMake
there are significant syntax hurdles you have to cross (mostly due to some legacy behavior they haven't dropped yet)
but once you realize the language is basically like a register machine instruction set (i.e. "functions" don't return values) it's pretty simple
I even wrote my own "object" syntax to access properties on mapped data, so I can define Gradle-like source sets and then get stored in a variable named "__${PROJECT_NAME}.srcs[${SET_NAME}]"
and if I want to access individual objects I've written load/store functions that map stuff like a variable called "main.srcDir" to "__${PROJECT_NAME}.srcs[main].srcDir"
(I've been thinking about writing a language that compiles to CMake, heh. A generator language for a build system generator language.)
I'd like to stay away from JVM in this case
